messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP path:
- /cms/log

Methods allowed (based on the code):
- all_methods: False
- HEAD: True
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False

Explanation
- Blueprint composition:
  - In app/__init__.py the CMS blueprint is registered on the app with url_prefix="/cms".
  - In app/api/cms/__init__.py the cms blueprint registers the log blueprint with url_prefix="/log".
  - In app/api/cms/log.py the route for get_logs is declared as @log_api.route("") — that attaches it to the log blueprint root. Combining prefixes yields /cms + /log + "" → /cms/log.

- HTTP methods:
  - The handler functions in log.py (get_logs, search_logs, get_users_for_log) use @log_api.route(...) without an explicit methods= argument, which means they are defined as GET handlers in the source code. Therefore GET is allowed.
  - Flask automatically provides HEAD for routes that accept GET (HEAD is implied by a GET route in Flask), so HEAD is considered acceptable based on the route definition.
  - Flask also provides automatic handling for OPTIONS (provide_automatic_options), so OPTIONS is acceptable.
  - There is no code declaring acceptance of POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, or TRACE for this route, so those are not acceptable. TRACE is not enabled by the route definition nor by Flask by default. 
- Note: There are two other routes in the same file mapped to /cms/log/search and /cms/log/users; they follow the same pattern (no explicit methods) and thus have the same method allowances (GET, HEAD, OPTIONS).
